19. Strategic Design

[00:00:00]

What's going on, crafters? Khalil here, and in this video, we're going to talk about strategic design, the next theoretical essential. Now, strategic design, traditionally, this concept comes from domain driven design, but Ultimately, the main idea here is we want to make very smart decisions about how we piece together our architecture.

At the end of the day, architecture is about the large scale decisions that we're going to make. And we make the majority of those decisions very early on in the project.

If we take a look at the guess points again, and if we look at the theoretical guess points, the ones that come first, this would seem to line up, wouldn't it?

Because so far we've talked about the problem guess point, we've talked about the solution guess point, and if we have clarity on what it is we're going to build, we know the features, we know the concrete examples, we even know the language, and perhaps even some of the lower level details like domain events and aggregates and business rules and so on and so forth.

The next thing to do is [00:01:00] for us to think about how we're going to realize this in the real world. The next thing for us to discuss is architecture.

Now making the shift from the solution guess point to the architecture guess point.

If we continue to think about this in terms of inputs and outputs What we're really getting from the solution guess point is this concept of the requirements Mostly the functional ones if we're talking about the examples But non functional requirements as well And non functional requirements are pretty much just about how the system should behave a little more qualitative.

They describe how the system should be. For example, how fast should it be?

How real time it should be, how many users we're expecting to be using it at a time. These important details come together and help us make decisions in terms of what we want to do for the architecture, and which architectural components we're going to need to use.

And that is one of the major problems, which is figuring out which components to use and not getting stuck, and making sure that we're making those good decisions.

There [00:02:00] are other questions we might be asking ourselves as well, such as how do you know what to build yourself versus something you should just go and install as an npm package or as an external service.

How do you integrate components together that just aren't integrating? And what do you do when there's a component you need, but you can't actually find it? There is no external service or something that's going to handle it for us. What do you do when you need this component, but it's not really fully related to the problem you're trying to solve?

What I found is that ultimately all developers need to know how to do four things in particular. The first is to stereotype components, which means you need to be able to look at a library, framework, tool, platform. Basically anything that is assistive that is going to help you to piece together your architecture, we'll call that an architectural component, and we need to be able to look at that and stereotype which aspects, which concerns, and which responsibilities does this architectural component come together to help us implement.

If we can [00:03:00] think about it at this level of granularity, the responsibility first level,which is actually the atomic deepest level that we could think about code from what I found,

then we'll be in a very good position to be able to stitch things together. Also coming from that point of view, we need the ability to develop components ourselves. So this is what takes us into this concept of Responsibility Driven Design.

Responsibility Driven Design is about seeing software as a

A bunch of just different responsibilities, which are doings and knowings, and those responsibilities get grouped into roles, and those roles collaborate with other responsibilities. And what happens is objects, or functions, or whatever the abstractions you're using as the syntactic sugar for an abstraction, whether you're taking an object oriented or functional approach,

Let's say objects for now, almost like a Broadway play where there's roles to play. They fill in for those roles and they play them and that is how software works. From a responsibility[00:04:00] driven design point of view.

Now there is a number of techniques we're going to have to learn such as the 3 step RDD process. This is the deepest level of design I can teach you. Once you learn it, you learn How to really design anything. Now, you're not always going to need to do this, but you will need to have the ability to drop in and actually piece together and design things out, thinking about the responsibilities and the stereotypical objects that connect and talk to each other.

And the reason why I need you to have this skill is because once I teach you that, there's very little else I could actually really teach you about design. that you won't be able to figure out yourself. In fact, there's been students who've gone through early versions of this course and gone through the mentorship training that when I taught them Responsibility Driven Design, they started to make sense of that.

That was pretty much it for them. They were off to the races and they could pretty much break down any problem that they were facing in terms of needing to know where things [00:05:00] belong, how to organize concerns, how big objects should be, how small objects should be, how many instance variables they should have.

All sorts of questions that typically plague the minds of most developers. These things, once you learn responsibility driven design, and we get here in the responsibility first phase of craftship, things will seem a lot more clearer to you.

The third thing we also need to learn how to do is integrate components. So sometimes you're going to need to use systems that don't actually talk to each other.

For example, when I was building out this course, I needed to somehow get the discord to talk to the course platform, and I didn't have a whole lot of time. So I needed to make some strategic smart moves in order to make that happen.

I was able to fill in a object design gap, or a responsibility gap as some call it, merely by just thinking things through from an object design perspective. And what I ended up rolling with is, if you've seen this already in the course, there is a form that you can [00:06:00] submit to get access to the community.

What's really going on there with that thing is I've just put some HTML that quickly shoots some code over to a hosted service which talks to the discord API.

These sorts of challenges are going to come up all over the place. I guarantee you, you're always going to need to figure out how to get one or two types of technologies to integrate properly.

And the big problem that a lot of developers have when they get. Past code first to best practice first to pattern first is that they're just thinking in terms of patterns And they don't actually know how to go deeper more low level and actually think strategically and think at the atomic level of design Which is the level of responsibilities?

And finally, the last thing you need to know how to do is to prioritize components.

So this is about knowing which contexts, which domains, which modules you actually

want to prioritize building. And generally, these are going to be the ones that lead to the most value in the business. Of course, sometimes you will be pressed in a [00:07:00] situation where you actually need to develop out something with these yourself.

Other times, you will be able to just use off the shelf things. For example, if I needed to somehow hook up SEO in my application I know that Next. js has some server side rendering as a part of that framework. So I could use that tool in addition with perhaps some other libraries in order to realize this sub aspect of building my system that has to do with SEO.

So strategic design is, as you would imagine, a little bit of an art, because it's about strategy, and it's about decision making, and the thing about decision making is it only gets better over time as you make more and more decisions, you learn more and more about what actually works and what doesn't work.

So as we move through the phases of craftship, we're going to use this technique a fair amount. We're going to use the responsibility driven design stuff in the responsibility first phase of craftship.

But in the best practice first phase of craftship, we're definitely going to have to use a little bit of strategic design to think through the way we build [00:08:00] things.

In the pattern first phase, it's going to absolutely be critical as we learn how to piece together our system as a set of

contexts that come together to help us solve the problems.

And when we get to the guess points and we talk a little bit more about the architecture guess point, that should also help you gain some more clarity on some of the techniques that we use and how those things piece together, which should help you with your final project as well.

So that's all I have to say for now about strategic design. We're going to get into it into more detail later on. So I'll leave the video right here for now. And with that being said, I'll see you in the next one. And as always, to mastery.
